WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:03.083
(bright music)

2
00:00:08.190 --> 00:00:12.090
<v Host>Dr. Vail is no stranger to board review.</v>

3
00:00:12.090 --> 00:00:14.550
Belinda is the chair in the Department of Family Medicine

4
00:00:14.550 --> 00:00:16.800
at the University of Kansas.

5
00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:19.740
And she is going to be leading our discussion

6
00:00:19.740 --> 00:00:21.600
on obesity and metabolic syndrome.

7
00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:23.310
So, Belinda, good morning, and take it away, ma'am.

8
00:00:23.310 --> 00:00:24.720
Thank you.
<v ->Thank you.</v>

9
00:00:24.720 --> 00:00:27.090
We're going to see the field of obesity medicine

10
00:00:27.090 --> 00:00:30.090
just change dramatically over the next few years.

11
00:00:30.090 --> 00:00:34.080
And what happens I think is totally up in the air.

12
00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:38.130
So we'll talk about the new weight loss drugs here.

13
00:00:38.130 --> 00:00:42.390
The obesity trend right now has been for years to just,

14
00:00:42.390 --> 00:00:44.280
the map has changed every year

15
00:00:44.280 --> 00:00:46.110
to get darker and darker and darker.

16
00:00:46.110 --> 00:00:48.090
They had to change the colors

17
00:00:48.090 --> 00:00:52.830
because we were just becoming as a nation, so rapidly obese.

18
00:00:52.830 --> 00:00:53.663
Notice on there,

19
00:00:53.663 --> 00:00:56.850
2/3 of Americans are either overweight or obese.

20
00:00:56.850 --> 00:00:59.643
So we have a lot, there's a lot of work to do.

21
00:01:00.583 --> 00:01:02.760
And he gave you the definitions.

22
00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:05.610
Overweight is a BMI of 25 or more.

23
00:01:05.610 --> 00:01:07.230
Obesity, 30 or more.

24
00:01:07.230 --> 00:01:11.400
In children, you have to use the graphs.

25
00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:16.400
It's 85 percentile for overweight, 95 percentile for obese.

26
00:01:16.410 --> 00:01:18.330
This is what the graph looks like.

27
00:01:18.330 --> 00:01:20.790
It's because in normal children,

28
00:01:20.790 --> 00:01:23.220
their BMI goes down to a nadir

29
00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:24.960
at about five or six years of age

30
00:01:24.960 --> 00:01:26.310
and then rises after that.

31
00:01:26.310 --> 00:01:28.410
So you have to use the graphs

32
00:01:28.410 --> 00:01:32.763
and use gender for this as well as age.

33
00:01:33.930 --> 00:01:35.280
Metabolic syndrome,

34
00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:37.980
please just know the definition of this.

35
00:01:37.980 --> 00:01:42.150
You have to have three of the five things

36
00:01:42.150 --> 00:01:45.453
that I have listed here to meet the criteria.

37
00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:49.590
There are a lot of different organizations who define this,

38
00:01:49.590 --> 00:01:52.110
so they may not use the exact same numbers,

39
00:01:52.110 --> 00:01:57.110
particularly for fasting glucose and for blood pressure.

40
00:01:57.780 --> 00:02:00.570
Those might be slightly different numbers,

41
00:02:00.570 --> 00:02:03.720
but they're all going to be using an elevated number.

42
00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:05.160
And pretty much everybody uses

43
00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:08.430
the same definitions for weight circumference,

44
00:02:08.430 --> 00:02:11.250
40 inches in men, 35 in women.

45
00:02:11.250 --> 00:02:16.110
And the same numbers for HDL and triglycerides.

46
00:02:16.110 --> 00:02:18.630
So what we're looking at is dyslipidemia,

47
00:02:18.630 --> 00:02:22.320
low HDL and high triglycerides.

48
00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:24.390
And so if you just have that dyslipidemia

49
00:02:24.390 --> 00:02:26.250
and only need one other thing to have,

50
00:02:26.250 --> 00:02:27.603
the metabolic syndrome.

51
00:02:28.770 --> 00:02:33.330
Also know the diagnose or the definition for prediabetes,

52
00:02:33.330 --> 00:02:37.110
it's an A1c of 5.7 to 6.4.

53
00:02:37.110 --> 00:02:38.460
It's pretty big.

54
00:02:38.460 --> 00:02:41.580
But what we're seeing with type 2 diabetes is

55
00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:44.250
a very insidious, slow onset.

56
00:02:44.250 --> 00:02:48.030
And so you don't have not diabetes and now diabetes.

57
00:02:48.030 --> 00:02:50.730
It's a progression to get there.

58
00:02:50.730 --> 00:02:54.150
And the quicker we interfere in that progression,

59
00:02:54.150 --> 00:02:56.133
the better off the patient is.

60
00:02:58.620 --> 00:03:01.560
The implications of obesity, we know those,

61
00:03:01.560 --> 00:03:03.270
there are a lot of them.

62
00:03:03.270 --> 00:03:06.510
You have a risk of a lot of different diseases,

63
00:03:06.510 --> 00:03:09.363
including the number one killers like heart disease.

64
00:03:10.710 --> 00:03:12.750
Please note on the cancers.

65
00:03:12.750 --> 00:03:16.050
Overall, if you look at all cancers,

66
00:03:16.050 --> 00:03:19.350
a lot of cancers are actually decreasing,

67
00:03:19.350 --> 00:03:22.380
but the obesity related cancers are increasing,

68
00:03:22.380 --> 00:03:23.550
and that's a number of them.

69
00:03:23.550 --> 00:03:26.760
All the female cancers are obesity related,

70
00:03:26.760 --> 00:03:28.893
particularly uterine cancer.

71
00:03:30.390 --> 00:03:34.560
And then the GI tract cancers are obesity related.

72
00:03:34.560 --> 00:03:37.020
And particularly gallbladder disease.

73
00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:41.460
And so gallbladder cancers are on the rise as well.

74
00:03:41.460 --> 00:03:42.360
And then you'll see

75
00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:45.900
there's kind of an odd conglomeration of other cancers

76
00:03:45.900 --> 00:03:47.100
that are obesity related,

77
00:03:47.100 --> 00:03:50.283
kidney, meningiomas, leukemia, and thyroid.

78
00:03:53.160 --> 00:03:57.120
We wanna start preventing obesity in childhood in the womb.

79
00:03:57.120 --> 00:03:59.160
So the less the mother gains,

80
00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:03.540
the less likely the child is to develop obesity

81
00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:04.950
later on in life.

82
00:04:04.950 --> 00:04:07.110
There are a lot of other things we can do,

83
00:04:07.110 --> 00:04:09.150
making sure they breastfeed,

84
00:04:09.150 --> 00:04:11.790
making sure they get that physical activity.

85
00:04:11.790 --> 00:04:14.753
And you see there,

86
00:04:14.753 --> 00:04:18.600
the two important things on this slide are the screening,

87
00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:20.580
which Dr. Weismiller noted.

88
00:04:20.580 --> 00:04:22.590
We screen everyone starting at six.

89
00:04:22.590 --> 00:04:25.357
That's USPSTF recommendation.

90
00:04:25.357 --> 00:04:30.357
And then we offer everyone these comprehensive programs,

91
00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:38.570
higher intensity, multicomponent behavioral programs,

92
00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:41.760
which require a lot of touch base with the patient.

93
00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:45.960
So again not you need to lose weight, see you in six months,

94
00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:48.240
but you need to lose weight, let's put you in a program,

95
00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:50.670
we're gonna talk to you every couple of weeks.

96
00:04:50.670 --> 00:04:51.600
That's sort of thing.

97
00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:54.783
That's the way to get patients to lose weight.

98
00:04:55.950 --> 00:04:58.410
43-year-old female has been struggling to lose weight.

99
00:04:58.410 --> 00:04:59.880
In reviewing her medications,

100
00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:02.430
which of the following is likely to be making weight loss

101
00:05:02.430 --> 00:05:04.620
substantially more difficult for her?

102
00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:08.853
Escitalopram, lisinopril, mirtazapine, or bupropion?

103
00:05:13.830 --> 00:05:15.510
Excellent, mirtazapine.

104
00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:17.520
And for some reason the boards like this,

105
00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:19.023
this particular one,

106
00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:22.560
you know, your patients always like to blame it on you.

107
00:05:22.560 --> 00:05:24.990
Well it's, you know, or their glands.

108
00:05:24.990 --> 00:05:27.540
You know, it's a gland problem that they have, you know?

109
00:05:27.540 --> 00:05:28.950
Yeah, so you don't eat it,

110
00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:32.160
you eat too much and you don't exercise enough,

111
00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:34.620
but I'm sure there's a gland problem as well.

112
00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:37.620
So but there are other reasons

113
00:05:37.620 --> 00:05:40.320
and we do need to check for those things.

114
00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:43.721
And we do give patients medications a lot

115
00:05:43.721 --> 00:05:46.770
that make it easier for them to gain weight.

116
00:05:46.770 --> 00:05:49.620
And so be thinking of medications that you can use

117
00:05:49.620 --> 00:05:51.060
that help them lose weight,

118
00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:53.280
not medications that make them gain.

119
00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:56.550
And so the anti-seizure meds are particularly bad.

120
00:05:56.550 --> 00:05:58.680
The second generation antipsychotics

121
00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:00.570
and the antidepressants.

122
00:06:00.570 --> 00:06:04.410
Most of the SSRIs are actually either weight neutral

123
00:06:04.410 --> 00:06:05.490
or help them lose.

124
00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:08.883
But be cautious in all of these.

125
00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:12.330
All right, diets.

126
00:06:12.330 --> 00:06:16.023
We could talk for the whole time just on diets.

127
00:06:17.250 --> 00:06:21.720
There's diets, some diets work for some people,

128
00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:23.583
some diets work for other people.

129
00:06:24.450 --> 00:06:27.000
Most diets are only effective

130
00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:30.270
for a reasonably short period of time.

131
00:06:30.270 --> 00:06:33.930
Usually about six months gets you maximum weight loss.

132
00:06:33.930 --> 00:06:37.080
And then sometimes people will continue

133
00:06:37.080 --> 00:06:39.750
to lose weight for up to two years.

134
00:06:39.750 --> 00:06:43.797
And then they tend to start gaining that weight back again.

135
00:06:43.797 --> 00:06:48.797
So diets are very difficult for patients to stay on.

136
00:06:49.350 --> 00:06:52.330
They need to change the relationship with food

137
00:06:53.910 --> 00:06:57.660
and their lifestyle and the way they live,

138
00:06:57.660 --> 00:07:00.210
not just the way they eat.

139
00:07:00.210 --> 00:07:01.980
So I'm just going to eat this.

140
00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:06.980
This is why diets like high-protein diets,

141
00:07:07.560 --> 00:07:10.200
you know, people tend to lose weight on those,

142
00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:12.330
but then over a period of time they're just,

143
00:07:12.330 --> 00:07:16.140
I can't stay on a diet.

144
00:07:16.140 --> 00:07:19.080
You can stay on a lifestyle change

145
00:07:19.080 --> 00:07:20.820
if you change the way you eat

146
00:07:20.820 --> 00:07:23.490
and you change your relationship with food.

147
00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:25.560
But when you have a diet,

148
00:07:25.560 --> 00:07:27.630
you have things that you can't eat

149
00:07:27.630 --> 00:07:28.980
and things that you can't do

150
00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:30.870
and that doesn't work for people,

151
00:07:30.870 --> 00:07:33.150
not over a long period of time.

152
00:07:33.150 --> 00:07:37.140
Please know the numbers of the kilocalories in a pound,

153
00:07:37.140 --> 00:07:40.260
there are 3,500 kilocalories in a pound.

154
00:07:40.260 --> 00:07:44.460
So if you cut your calories 500 a day for seven days,

155
00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:48.660
that's 3,500, that's a pound, okay?

156
00:07:48.660 --> 00:07:53.310
And I actually one time on the boards had to calculate that.

157
00:07:53.310 --> 00:07:55.800
So a 27-year-old female with a BMI of 39

158
00:07:55.800 --> 00:07:56.820
requests help with the diet.

159
00:07:56.820 --> 00:07:58.470
You tell her there's no weight loss diet

160
00:07:58.470 --> 00:07:59.460
that's better than the others.

161
00:07:59.460 --> 00:08:02.250
The Mediterranean diet is the best weight loss diet.

162
00:08:02.250 --> 00:08:04.470
Decreasing intake by 500 calories a day

163
00:08:04.470 --> 00:08:07.200
will result in the recommended two-pound weekly weight loss.

164
00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:09.630
And avoid the commercial weight loss programs

165
00:08:09.630 --> 00:08:11.463
because they don't produce results.

166
00:08:17.310 --> 00:08:18.270
Very good.

167
00:08:18.270 --> 00:08:21.270
There just is no diet that's like the,

168
00:08:21.270 --> 00:08:23.940
you know, the panacea diet.

169
00:08:23.940 --> 00:08:27.390
And every year, every magazine you pick up,

170
00:08:27.390 --> 00:08:28.290
there's a new diet,

171
00:08:28.290 --> 00:08:30.363
every year there's a new fad diet.

172
00:08:31.470 --> 00:08:35.820
The Mediterranean diet is the best diet.

173
00:08:35.820 --> 00:08:39.600
So there are variations of the Mediterranean diet.

174
00:08:39.600 --> 00:08:41.821
The DASH diet is one of those.

175
00:08:41.821 --> 00:08:46.080
The new one, the rave this year's the portfolio diet.

176
00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:48.360
So it's much, it's a plant-based,

177
00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:51.750
a lot of plant protein, not so much animal protein,

178
00:08:51.750 --> 00:08:54.483
but it's not a total vegetarian diet.

179
00:08:55.920 --> 00:08:59.160
Again, those very low carbohydrate diets are,

180
00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:01.740
if you want rapid weight gain, they're the best,

181
00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:05.493
but they tend to not be able to be sustained.

182
00:09:06.690 --> 00:09:10.860
In kids, we know that diet alone, exercise alone,

183
00:09:10.860 --> 00:09:13.830
neither of those work anywhere nearly as well

184
00:09:13.830 --> 00:09:15.600
as putting the two together.

185
00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:19.470
And this eating meals as a family every day has been shown

186
00:09:19.470 --> 00:09:24.240
to really improve patients' perception of themselves,

187
00:09:24.240 --> 00:09:26.100
we're talking kids and teens here.

188
00:09:26.100 --> 00:09:30.300
And looking at better attitudes about food.

189
00:09:30.300 --> 00:09:31.203
And so,

190
00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:34.890
we're seeing more and more weight loss programs now

191
00:09:34.890 --> 00:09:37.860
concentrating on the family unit.

192
00:09:37.860 --> 00:09:41.220
So parent and child dyads

193
00:09:41.220 --> 00:09:43.710
and not just let's pick the child out

194
00:09:43.710 --> 00:09:45.660
and try to get them to lose weight.

195
00:09:45.660 --> 00:09:48.633
It really, it's a family affair, it truly is.

196
00:09:49.590 --> 00:09:52.830
For diabetes, these are the changes that are helpful,

197
00:09:52.830 --> 00:09:55.080
again, a Mediterranean style diet.

198
00:09:55.080 --> 00:09:59.190
More seafood, whole grains, fruits, veggies, low fat dairy,

199
00:09:59.190 --> 00:10:01.920
more potassium, calcium, vitamin D, magnesium,

200
00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:04.980
and particularly B12 in the diet.

201
00:10:04.980 --> 00:10:06.810
It's better to put things in the diet

202
00:10:06.810 --> 00:10:08.850
than to put them into a pill.

203
00:10:08.850 --> 00:10:11.583
So if you can get them in the diet much, much better.

204
00:10:13.170 --> 00:10:16.080
So you have a 37-year-old male with a BMI of 35

205
00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:18.810
and would like to lose weight without changing his diet,

206
00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:22.170
but with daily moderate-intensity exercise, you tell him.

207
00:10:22.170 --> 00:10:24.930
He should not expect to lose weight with exercise alone.

208
00:10:24.930 --> 00:10:26.340
If he adds dietary changes,

209
00:10:26.340 --> 00:10:28.740
he will likely have substantial weight loss.

210
00:10:28.740 --> 00:10:30.360
Adding exercise will likely be

211
00:10:30.360 --> 00:10:32.610
moderately beneficial for weight loss.

212
00:10:32.610 --> 00:10:35.580
Or he should expect significant weight loss

213
00:10:35.580 --> 00:10:38.193
if he exercises daily for at least 60 minutes.

214
00:10:43.560 --> 00:10:47.415
Well, when we're talking about diet and exercise,

215
00:10:47.415 --> 00:10:50.553
if the word moderate is in it, you should pick that.

216
00:10:51.432 --> 00:10:54.600
Because substantial just doesn't,

217
00:10:54.600 --> 00:10:57.240
diet and exercise just doesn't get you substantial

218
00:10:57.240 --> 00:10:58.770
in most cases.

219
00:10:58.770 --> 00:11:02.220
So adding exercise will be moderately beneficial.

220
00:11:02.220 --> 00:11:03.540
And here again,

221
00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:05.700
the number that you're gonna see over and over on the boards

222
00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:09.210
is 150 minutes a week of moderate exercise.

223
00:11:09.210 --> 00:11:12.750
Moderate exercise, that's the recommendation.

224
00:11:12.750 --> 00:11:14.220
Again, if you're going to lose weight,

225
00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:15.690
you're gonna have to bump that up.

226
00:11:15.690 --> 00:11:18.300
And there was just a study out that showed

227
00:11:18.300 --> 00:11:23.300
that 300 minutes a week is what you really need

228
00:11:23.610 --> 00:11:27.990
to have peak effect on your cardiovascular.

229
00:11:27.990 --> 00:11:30.900
So, and for the most healthy,

230
00:11:30.900 --> 00:11:32.880
you need to get to 300 minutes a week.

231
00:11:32.880 --> 00:11:37.560
And it was it effective,

232
00:11:37.560 --> 00:11:40.800
much more so for women than for men.

233
00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:43.140
So that was an interesting finding.

234
00:11:43.140 --> 00:11:45.813
So more important for the women than for the men.

235
00:11:48.180 --> 00:11:50.280
And you can see I've given you a few other things there.

236
00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:52.080
Lots of advantages to exercise.

237
00:11:52.080 --> 00:11:54.270
It makes us healthier overall.

238
00:11:54.270 --> 00:11:56.100
And if you do, athletes,

239
00:11:56.100 --> 00:11:58.959
make sure that this is particularly for type 1 diabetics,

240
00:11:58.959 --> 00:12:02.250
if they're getting ready to play a game

241
00:12:02.250 --> 00:12:03.950
and their glucose is over 300

242
00:12:03.950 --> 00:12:07.920
or over 250 with ketones in their urine, they cannot play

243
00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:11.580
because they have a shortage of insulin.

244
00:12:11.580 --> 00:12:14.043
They need insulin not exercise at that point.

245
00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.823
All right, weight loss maintenance.

246
00:12:19.290 --> 00:12:21.930
This has been an odd question that's appeared

247
00:12:21.930 --> 00:12:25.950
and the answer has been to eat breakfast daily.

248
00:12:25.950 --> 00:12:28.110
I don't think that's going to appear anymore.

249
00:12:28.110 --> 00:12:30.300
People have moved around that now

250
00:12:30.300 --> 00:12:32.490
with a lot more eating when you're hungry

251
00:12:32.490 --> 00:12:34.323
and satiety sort of things.

252
00:12:35.460 --> 00:12:39.224
Monitoring the weight once a week is really important.

253
00:12:39.224 --> 00:12:41.040
And they tend to try to put in there

254
00:12:41.040 --> 00:12:43.440
that you should monitor your weight daily,

255
00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:45.000
and that's not the answer.

256
00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.490
The answer is monitor once a week.

257
00:12:47.490 --> 00:12:49.200
So you wanna keep an eye on it,

258
00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:50.880
but you don't have to look at it every day,

259
00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:52.413
your weight changes daily.

260
00:12:54.600 --> 00:12:56.520
I think the other's straightforward.

261
00:12:56.520 --> 00:12:58.980
Okay, let's get to the medicines.

262
00:12:58.980 --> 00:13:03.720
Medicines are indicated for a BMI of 30 or 27

263
00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:07.470
if you have another comorbid condition like diabetes.

264
00:13:07.470 --> 00:13:09.900
So in general,

265
00:13:09.900 --> 00:13:12.660
we're using only the approved weight loss medications.

266
00:13:12.660 --> 00:13:15.060
I'll give you a couple of caveats there.

267
00:13:15.060 --> 00:13:17.160
You need to monitor these every month

268
00:13:17.160 --> 00:13:18.240
for the first three months

269
00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:21.600
and then at least every three months after that.

270
00:13:21.600 --> 00:13:23.620
And only continue weight loss

271
00:13:24.602 --> 00:13:25.680
or continue the medications,

272
00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:28.473
if they're actively losing on the medications.

273
00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:33.690
In prediabetes, we use things like metformin, pioglitazone.

274
00:13:33.690 --> 00:13:36.030
Remember that statins actually

275
00:13:36.030 --> 00:13:38.730
increase your risk of diabetes.

276
00:13:38.730 --> 00:13:43.680
And they are not for weight loss, this is for heart health.

277
00:13:43.680 --> 00:13:46.320
There are things that delay the onset of diabetes.

278
00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:47.730
And that's been a question.

279
00:13:47.730 --> 00:13:51.000
And the answer is lifestyle, lifestyle, lifestyle.

280
00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:52.800
So there are a lot of meds that do it,

281
00:13:52.800 --> 00:13:54.693
but lifestyle is the answer.

282
00:13:56.070 --> 00:14:00.030
The SGLT-2 inhibitors are out there now.

283
00:14:00.030 --> 00:14:04.983
And you're going to see the GLP-1s on that list as well.

284
00:14:06.150 --> 00:14:09.900
In general, if you're picking medications for other things,

285
00:14:09.900 --> 00:14:11.970
pick weight loss type medications.

286
00:14:11.970 --> 00:14:14.280
So if your patient has migraines

287
00:14:14.280 --> 00:14:16.530
and you wanna use migraine prophylaxis,

288
00:14:16.530 --> 00:14:18.120
topiramate is a great choice

289
00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:21.390
because it's a good weight loss drug, okay?

290
00:14:21.390 --> 00:14:23.280
Bupropion if they have depression

291
00:14:23.280 --> 00:14:25.620
because they're gonna be more likely to lose weight on that

292
00:14:25.620 --> 00:14:26.970
than anything else.

293
00:14:26.970 --> 00:14:31.170
And then again, the GLP-1s and the SGLT-2s.

294
00:14:31.170 --> 00:14:33.423
We're gonna talk a lot about those today.

295
00:14:34.830 --> 00:14:37.740
A 57-year-old female with a BMI of 37 has tried

296
00:14:37.740 --> 00:14:40.020
six months of intensive behavioral weight management

297
00:14:40.020 --> 00:14:42.090
and has only lost seven pounds.

298
00:14:42.090 --> 00:14:43.530
Seen that a few times.

299
00:14:43.530 --> 00:14:46.470
She's adequately treated hypertension and diabetes

300
00:14:46.470 --> 00:14:47.820
with an A1c in the eight range.

301
00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:49.860
What would be her best choice for weight loss?

302
00:14:49.860 --> 00:14:53.640
Topiramate, phentermine, orlistat, or semaglutide?

303
00:14:53.640 --> 00:14:56.133
This should take all of three seconds to answer.

304
00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:03.570
You bet, semaglutide.

305
00:15:03.570 --> 00:15:08.193
And these drugs are revolutionizing what we're doing.

306
00:15:09.120 --> 00:15:12.090
Okay, so these are the licensed weight loss medications.

307
00:15:12.090 --> 00:15:14.040
Orlistat, it's been out there for a long time.

308
00:15:14.040 --> 00:15:17.880
It blocks a breakdown of fat in the gut,

309
00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:19.740
and so you don't absorb fats,

310
00:15:19.740 --> 00:15:22.140
so they go out in your bowels,

311
00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:23.700
along with all kinds of bacteria

312
00:15:23.700 --> 00:15:26.790
and there's all kinds of GI side effects.

313
00:15:26.790 --> 00:15:29.280
Weight loss is fairly moderate with this,

314
00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:31.920
but it can be used long term.

315
00:15:31.920 --> 00:15:33.660
I will tell you that over the counter,

316
00:15:33.660 --> 00:15:36.780
it works just as well as the prescription.

317
00:15:36.780 --> 00:15:40.230
And you can get this, it's called Alli,

318
00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:42.483
you can get it pretty much any place.

319
00:15:43.980 --> 00:15:46.530
Okay, bupropion and naltrexone,

320
00:15:46.530 --> 00:15:50.250
that combination, these drugs are actually pretty expensive.

321
00:15:50.250 --> 00:15:52.260
They cost, these you know are costing

322
00:15:52.260 --> 00:15:55.530
the five, $600 range, interestingly.

323
00:15:55.530 --> 00:16:00.530
And they work reasonably well.

324
00:16:00.810 --> 00:16:03.840
Again, you can use bupropion anyway,

325
00:16:03.840 --> 00:16:06.579
but the combination works a little better.

326
00:16:06.579 --> 00:16:08.863
It works pretty well for those people

327
00:16:08.863 --> 00:16:11.040
who kind of tend to, you know,

328
00:16:11.040 --> 00:16:14.730
like when they do eat, they just eat too much.

329
00:16:14.730 --> 00:16:15.563
And that, you know,

330
00:16:15.563 --> 00:16:17.010
the ones that they, I don't, you know,

331
00:16:17.010 --> 00:16:18.540
I eat three meals a day.

332
00:16:18.540 --> 00:16:20.970
Well, you eat, you know, some of them too big.

333
00:16:20.970 --> 00:16:25.970
So this is a reasonable drug in that category.

334
00:16:27.210 --> 00:16:30.390
Okay, phentermine has been around for a long, long time

335
00:16:30.390 --> 00:16:33.480
and it is the only cheap medication on the list.

336
00:16:33.480 --> 00:16:37.920
And it's an amphetamine derivative.

337
00:16:37.920 --> 00:16:40.800
You can see we usually use it

338
00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:44.250
at doses up to 37.5 milligrams a day.

339
00:16:44.250 --> 00:16:47.280
There is a new formulation now that's eight milligrams.

340
00:16:47.280 --> 00:16:49.320
And so using that

341
00:16:49.320 --> 00:16:54.320
in combination with phentermine or with topiramate

342
00:16:54.690 --> 00:16:57.450
will sometimes give you pretty much the same thing

343
00:16:57.450 --> 00:17:01.083
as the phentermine topiramate Qsymia combination.

344
00:17:01.950 --> 00:17:04.530
And because again, that drug costs about $600

345
00:17:04.530 --> 00:17:07.563
and isn't very often covered by their insurance.

346
00:17:08.400 --> 00:17:11.490
Until the new injectable medications came out,

347
00:17:11.490 --> 00:17:14.520
this was really the best one on the list.

348
00:17:14.520 --> 00:17:17.730
The side effects are the mostly from the topiramate.

349
00:17:17.730 --> 00:17:21.090
And so patients feel a little odd on topiramate sometimes.

350
00:17:21.090 --> 00:17:23.670
So sometimes you have to start that dose pretty low.

351
00:17:23.670 --> 00:17:26.610
So the GLP-1s.

352
00:17:26.610 --> 00:17:30.420
GLP-1 is a substance in your blood or in your,

353
00:17:30.420 --> 00:17:33.270
it's secreted from the pancreas

354
00:17:33.270 --> 00:17:37.620
and it helps you to secrete insulin.

355
00:17:37.620 --> 00:17:41.550
It increases satiety, it slows gastric emptying,

356
00:17:41.550 --> 00:17:43.920
so your stomach feels full longer.

357
00:17:43.920 --> 00:17:45.750
And often it is full longer.

358
00:17:45.750 --> 00:17:48.783
There are, we have to talk about the complications of this.

359
00:17:50.070 --> 00:17:52.500
So the first drug out in this category

360
00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:54.720
that was used for weight loss was liraglutide,

361
00:17:54.720 --> 00:17:56.460
it's a daily injection.

362
00:17:56.460 --> 00:17:59.160
And so then semaglutide came out

363
00:17:59.160 --> 00:18:00.570
and it's a weekly injection.

364
00:18:00.570 --> 00:18:03.060
That's a lot easier sell for people.

365
00:18:03.060 --> 00:18:07.350
So, and people are lining up like crazy to get these drugs.

366
00:18:07.350 --> 00:18:12.350
But look at that, 86.4% have at least a 5% weight loss.

367
00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:17.700
We had nothing that gave this in the past.

368
00:18:17.700 --> 00:18:21.630
So out of the gate, this was,

369
00:18:21.630 --> 00:18:25.740
this quickly became a high demand drug.

370
00:18:25.740 --> 00:18:29.730
Tirzepatide is the newest, it's a GLP-1,

371
00:18:29.730 --> 00:18:34.730
and a glucagon-dependent insulinotropic peptide.

372
00:18:34.920 --> 00:18:37.710
So it works in two different ways.

373
00:18:37.710 --> 00:18:42.480
And you can look at the average weight loss there of 21%.

374
00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:44.013
So this is a, look,

375
00:18:45.210 --> 00:18:47.460
and there is a third generation coming out

376
00:18:47.460 --> 00:18:50.040
that will work in three ways.

377
00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:53.220
It's a GLP-1, a GIP, and another mechanism.

378
00:18:53.220 --> 00:18:57.900
And so we're gonna see these drugs just pound the market.

379
00:18:57.900 --> 00:18:59.793
Zepbound came out.

380
00:19:00.750 --> 00:19:04.350
So tirzepatide has been out, as Mounjaro for diabetes,

381
00:19:04.350 --> 00:19:07.650
it came out as Zepbound in December.

382
00:19:07.650 --> 00:19:10.650
Most insurance companies are not covering it yet.

383
00:19:10.650 --> 00:19:13.893
So, but that will happen over the next few months.

384
00:19:16.080 --> 00:19:18.783
Weight loss medications in children and adolescents.

385
00:19:20.460 --> 00:19:25.460
The pediatrics association is really pushing

386
00:19:26.070 --> 00:19:28.590
to get medications into children,

387
00:19:28.590 --> 00:19:33.590
to get to think about bariatric options for children,

388
00:19:34.080 --> 00:19:36.360
about bariatric surgery.

389
00:19:36.360 --> 00:19:41.360
Because we know that when children are obese as children

390
00:19:41.610 --> 00:19:44.670
and maintain that obesity into adulthood,

391
00:19:44.670 --> 00:19:47.280
they have increased morbidity and mortality

392
00:19:47.280 --> 00:19:50.010
throughout their lifetimes so.

393
00:19:50.010 --> 00:19:53.190
In children, medication options are orlistat,

394
00:19:53.190 --> 00:19:54.990
the phentermine topiramate,

395
00:19:54.990 --> 00:19:57.480
and both liraglutide and semaglutide.

396
00:19:57.480 --> 00:20:01.623
And I'm sure that tirzepatide will join that list soon.

397
00:20:03.270 --> 00:20:04.680
This is just really quickly,

398
00:20:04.680 --> 00:20:07.320
I wanted to tell you about this gastric balloon

399
00:20:07.320 --> 00:20:08.490
because you may see it.

400
00:20:08.490 --> 00:20:09.840
They're using it in odd places,

401
00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:12.660
like I've seen plastic surgery offices using this.

402
00:20:12.660 --> 00:20:15.180
And you put a balloon down into the stomach

403
00:20:15.180 --> 00:20:16.440
and fill it up with water,

404
00:20:16.440 --> 00:20:19.722
so it fills up the stomach and effectively makes you have,

405
00:20:19.722 --> 00:20:24.450
you know, it's kind of a bariatric surgery alternative.

406
00:20:24.450 --> 00:20:27.930
And then after about three to four months,

407
00:20:27.930 --> 00:20:29.490
the balloon usually bursts

408
00:20:29.490 --> 00:20:33.180
and then is passed out in the feces.

409
00:20:33.180 --> 00:20:35.910
Sometimes it gets caught

410
00:20:35.910 --> 00:20:38.587
and they have to surgically retrieve it.

411
00:20:38.587 --> 00:20:41.430
So there are some complications with this.

412
00:20:41.430 --> 00:20:43.740
And it really has never become mainline,

413
00:20:43.740 --> 00:20:46.440
but I just wanted you to know it's out there.

414
00:20:46.440 --> 00:20:49.230
Okay, let's talk about bariatric surgery.

415
00:20:49.230 --> 00:20:53.100
It is the most effective form of weight loss.

416
00:20:53.100 --> 00:20:56.133
And don't be surprised if you see that question.

417
00:20:57.180 --> 00:21:00.660
It's not the best form, it's the most effective form.

418
00:21:00.660 --> 00:21:04.050
If you do bariatric surgery, people lose weight.

419
00:21:04.050 --> 00:21:05.940
It's very effective.

420
00:21:05.940 --> 00:21:07.620
It's a very effective option

421
00:21:07.620 --> 00:21:09.690
for treatment of type 2 diabetes.

422
00:21:09.690 --> 00:21:12.780
And it has reduced all cause mortality,

423
00:21:12.780 --> 00:21:15.450
particularly cardiac mortality.

424
00:21:15.450 --> 00:21:20.340
And so people do better after bariatric surgery.

425
00:21:20.340 --> 00:21:22.350
It's indicated with a BMI of

426
00:21:22.350 --> 00:21:26.820
greater than 40 or greater than 35 with other complications

427
00:21:26.820 --> 00:21:29.763
or greater than 30 with uncontrolled diabetes.

428
00:21:31.050 --> 00:21:35.910
So, you should offer it after everything else has failed.

429
00:21:35.910 --> 00:21:38.760
So you should try medications first.

430
00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:42.423
It's high risk for obesity related,

431
00:21:43.350 --> 00:21:44.400
anybody who's at high risk

432
00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:47.010
for obesity related morbidity and mortality.

433
00:21:47.010 --> 00:21:50.610
Generally indicated between the ages of 18 and 65,

434
00:21:50.610 --> 00:21:54.090
but they've really pushed the ranges on this.

435
00:21:54.090 --> 00:21:57.120
And you can see the contraindications there,

436
00:21:57.120 --> 00:21:59.700
substance use, end stage disease.

437
00:21:59.700 --> 00:22:02.530
So any kind of end stage organ disease is

438
00:22:02.530 --> 00:22:04.203
gonna be contraindicated.

439
00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:07.320
But look at the outcomes,

440
00:22:07.320 --> 00:22:09.780
80% less likely develop diabetes

441
00:22:09.780 --> 00:22:13.530
and all less major adverse liver outcomes,

442
00:22:13.530 --> 00:22:15.870
adverse cardiac outcomes,

443
00:22:15.870 --> 00:22:20.220
much more mean weight loss with this

444
00:22:20.220 --> 00:22:23.539
as compared to a non-surgical group.

445
00:22:23.539 --> 00:22:28.539
So this is a very effective form of treatment.

446
00:22:29.130 --> 00:22:32.130
You have a 46-year-old considering a sleeve gastrectomy,

447
00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:35.010
what should you tell her is the most likely complication

448
00:22:35.010 --> 00:22:36.663
in the first six months?

449
00:22:38.640 --> 00:22:41.973
Pulmonary embolus, GERD, reoperation, or dumping syndrome?

450
00:22:48.840 --> 00:22:51.093
All right, good, GERD.

451
00:22:51.093 --> 00:22:55.500
The dumping syndrome is not that common.

452
00:22:55.500 --> 00:22:57.630
It does occur,

453
00:22:57.630 --> 00:23:00.270
but it's not nearly as common as some of these other things.

454
00:23:00.270 --> 00:23:01.530
So first of all,

455
00:23:01.530 --> 00:23:05.850
the complications right after bariatric surgery

456
00:23:05.850 --> 00:23:07.503
are actually very low.

457
00:23:08.430 --> 00:23:12.480
The lowest complication rate is with the sleeve gastrectomy,

458
00:23:12.480 --> 00:23:16.140
which has now become the number one treatment

459
00:23:16.140 --> 00:23:17.700
in bariatric surgery.

460
00:23:17.700 --> 00:23:21.240
Notice that now sleeve gastrectomy or Roux-en-Y,

461
00:23:21.240 --> 00:23:23.730
either one can be done laparoscopically.

462
00:23:23.730 --> 00:23:28.200
And so that's really moved this area of medicine forward.

463
00:23:28.200 --> 00:23:32.760
But please know the number one cause of death,

464
00:23:32.760 --> 00:23:35.190
cause of death not complication,

465
00:23:35.190 --> 00:23:38.400
but cause of death immediately following bariatric surgery

466
00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:40.320
is pulmonary embolus.

467
00:23:40.320 --> 00:23:42.690
And that's a question that's frequently asked,

468
00:23:42.690 --> 00:23:44.250
so please know that.

469
00:23:44.250 --> 00:23:46.650
Okay, the biggest complications, right?

470
00:23:46.650 --> 00:23:48.840
It depends on where you look.

471
00:23:48.840 --> 00:23:52.890
GERD and gallbladder problems.

472
00:23:52.890 --> 00:23:55.830
And a lot of cases they'll take out the gallbladder

473
00:23:55.830 --> 00:23:58.230
when they do the surgery

474
00:23:58.230 --> 00:24:02.550
because when you lose weight you have gallbladder problems.

475
00:24:02.550 --> 00:24:04.920
So how much of it is from the bariatric surgery itself

476
00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:05.910
and how much of it is from

477
00:24:05.910 --> 00:24:07.804
the weight loss that occurs after.

478
00:24:07.804 --> 00:24:11.490
It all gets lost in the mass.

479
00:24:11.490 --> 00:24:14.880
But those two things are going to be

480
00:24:14.880 --> 00:24:17.250
your greatest complication rates.

481
00:24:17.250 --> 00:24:20.040
So dumping syndrome is not that common

482
00:24:20.040 --> 00:24:23.730
and it's going to be much more common in bypass procedures,

483
00:24:23.730 --> 00:24:27.813
like in Roux-en-Y not in a sleeve gastrectomy.

484
00:24:29.160 --> 00:24:30.600
Nutritional deficiencies,

485
00:24:30.600 --> 00:24:32.850
please know it's iron deficiency.

486
00:24:32.850 --> 00:24:36.420
That's the number one nutritional deficiency.

487
00:24:36.420 --> 00:24:39.210
We talk about a lot of others, but that's the number one.

488
00:24:39.210 --> 00:24:41.370
You can see some of the other issues there.

489
00:24:41.370 --> 00:24:43.890
So this is the sleeve gastrectomy.

490
00:24:43.890 --> 00:24:46.290
They just basically make the stomach a tube

491
00:24:46.290 --> 00:24:49.050
and in doing that they get rid of the antrum of the stomach.

492
00:24:49.050 --> 00:24:50.880
And so they also get rid of,

493
00:24:50.880 --> 00:24:54.750
that's where most of the hunger hormone ghrelin comes from.

494
00:24:54.750 --> 00:24:57.450
And because you don't have any ghrelin,

495
00:24:57.450 --> 00:25:01.320
then you get hungry less often.

496
00:25:01.320 --> 00:25:05.940
And so that's an added benefit of the sleeve gastrectomy.

497
00:25:05.940 --> 00:25:07.920
The weight loss tends to be a little slower

498
00:25:07.920 --> 00:25:09.420
than with a Roux-en-Y.

499
00:25:09.420 --> 00:25:12.210
There's not a malabsorptive component here,

500
00:25:12.210 --> 00:25:16.050
so you tend to get fewer of the deficiencies

501
00:25:16.050 --> 00:25:19.203
or things like dumping syndrome that sort of thing.

502
00:25:20.430 --> 00:25:21.450
Here's the Roux-en-Y.

503
00:25:21.450 --> 00:25:23.490
You make the stomach really small,

504
00:25:23.490 --> 00:25:25.320
you cut the end of the duodenum,

505
00:25:25.320 --> 00:25:27.750
you bring it up and attach it to the stomach.

506
00:25:27.750 --> 00:25:31.410
And then you have to attach that whole stomach,

507
00:25:31.410 --> 00:25:33.720
first part of the duodenum back in

508
00:25:33.720 --> 00:25:34.553
because that's where

509
00:25:34.553 --> 00:25:36.600
all of our digestive juices come from, right?

510
00:25:36.600 --> 00:25:39.810
So you have to get that all back in there.

511
00:25:39.810 --> 00:25:42.270
But note that this is the recommended surgery

512
00:25:42.270 --> 00:25:45.030
in patients with pre-existent GERD.

513
00:25:45.030 --> 00:25:47.100
This is an A recommendation

514
00:25:47.100 --> 00:25:49.620
and has already been asked on the In-Training Exam.

515
00:25:49.620 --> 00:25:51.153
So please know that.

516
00:25:52.920 --> 00:25:56.340
After bariatric surgery, avoid NSAIDs.

517
00:25:56.340 --> 00:25:57.630
For a while they were saying

518
00:25:57.630 --> 00:25:59.160
you could never take NSAIDs again

519
00:25:59.160 --> 00:26:00.480
if you had bariatric surgery.

520
00:26:00.480 --> 00:26:03.300
They really relaxed that.

521
00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:05.880
But for the first few months after bariatric surgery,

522
00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:08.040
you need to have no NSAIDs,

523
00:26:08.040 --> 00:26:12.960
insulin secretagogues like the sulfonylureas,

524
00:26:12.960 --> 00:26:15.450
try to get patients off of anything like that.

525
00:26:15.450 --> 00:26:17.550
You're gonna decrease your insulin doses

526
00:26:17.550 --> 00:26:19.230
because they're gonna lose weight

527
00:26:19.230 --> 00:26:22.260
and their diabetes is gonna get in better control.

528
00:26:22.260 --> 00:26:23.970
You can't use extended release

529
00:26:23.970 --> 00:26:26.070
or enteric-coated medications.

530
00:26:26.070 --> 00:26:27.180
So you're gonna need to look

531
00:26:27.180 --> 00:26:29.880
through their whole medication group

532
00:26:29.880 --> 00:26:31.770
and make sure you get them off of those

533
00:26:31.770 --> 00:26:33.783
extended release medications.

534
00:26:34.650 --> 00:26:37.890
And pregnancy should be avoided for at least a year

535
00:26:37.890 --> 00:26:40.440
following bariatric surgery.

536
00:26:40.440 --> 00:26:43.740
So meal recommendations, they need to eat small amounts,

537
00:26:43.740 --> 00:26:45.240
they need to, they can't,

538
00:26:45.240 --> 00:26:46.470
it's all they can eat.

539
00:26:46.470 --> 00:26:48.690
And they need to eat their protein first

540
00:26:48.690 --> 00:26:50.370
so they make sure they get their protein.

541
00:26:50.370 --> 00:26:53.610
You don't consume liquids when you're eating your meals.

542
00:26:53.610 --> 00:26:58.353
And then the vitamin supplementation is probably indefinite.

543
00:27:00.210 --> 00:27:04.890
Labs, you have to get frequent labs in the first year.

544
00:27:04.890 --> 00:27:06.780
Then there's a lot of controversy about

545
00:27:06.780 --> 00:27:09.420
how often we should be getting these.

546
00:27:09.420 --> 00:27:12.090
Right now, the recommendation is yearly

547
00:27:12.090 --> 00:27:14.100
after the first couple of years.

548
00:27:14.100 --> 00:27:15.540
But look at all of those things,

549
00:27:15.540 --> 00:27:18.720
all of those vitamins and the supplementation.

550
00:27:18.720 --> 00:27:20.820
They're also backing off on the supplementation

551
00:27:20.820 --> 00:27:21.930
on some of these things

552
00:27:21.930 --> 00:27:25.620
and not looking for some of them like copper for instance,

553
00:27:25.620 --> 00:27:27.660
for a while they were looking for all of these

554
00:27:27.660 --> 00:27:29.190
on a regular basis.

555
00:27:29.190 --> 00:27:31.920
And please note that they should have a bone density

556
00:27:31.920 --> 00:27:35.253
a couple of years after their bariatric surgery as well.

557
00:27:36.300 --> 00:27:39.240
So bariatric surgery works.

558
00:27:39.240 --> 00:27:41.250
60 to 80% of obese patients have

559
00:27:41.250 --> 00:27:43.740
complete resolution of their diabetes.

560
00:27:43.740 --> 00:27:48.740
And 30% still had resolution at 15 years with Roux-en-Y.

561
00:27:48.930 --> 00:27:52.050
That's a pretty amazing.

562
00:27:52.050 --> 00:27:55.230
And the mortality rate is three to four times higher

563
00:27:55.230 --> 00:27:58.470
in patients treated with oral medications in diabetes

564
00:27:58.470 --> 00:28:00.750
as opposed to those who have bariatric surgery.

565
00:28:00.750 --> 00:28:04.170
It saves lives for people who are morbidly obese.

566
00:28:04.170 --> 00:28:05.700
All right, we're gonna quickly talk

567
00:28:05.700 --> 00:28:07.260
about screening for diabetes.

568
00:28:07.260 --> 00:28:09.660
The USPSTF recommends screening for diabetes

569
00:28:09.660 --> 00:28:11.100
in which of the following groups?

570
00:28:11.100 --> 00:28:13.680
All persons age 35 to 70 who are overweight,

571
00:28:13.680 --> 00:28:15.660
all persons with a BMI greater than 30,

572
00:28:15.660 --> 00:28:17.550
all obese persons beginning at age 35,

573
00:28:17.550 --> 00:28:20.343
or all children above the 80th per 85th percentile.

574
00:28:30.510 --> 00:28:31.950
Okay, this one's very important.

575
00:28:31.950 --> 00:28:33.990
It's a USPSTF recommendation.

576
00:28:33.990 --> 00:28:38.640
So everybody, 35 to 70 who's overweight or obese.

577
00:28:38.640 --> 00:28:41.490
And also the ADA recommends screening all women

578
00:28:41.490 --> 00:28:45.090
with gestational diabetes at four to 12 weeks postpartum.

579
00:28:45.090 --> 00:28:46.740
These are the ADA recommendations.

580
00:28:46.740 --> 00:28:48.030
You can look at those.

581
00:28:48.030 --> 00:28:50.411
I just want you to know that these have been

582
00:28:50.411 --> 00:28:54.870
the recommendations for screening for diabetes in children,

583
00:28:54.870 --> 00:28:58.380
but the USPSTF just came out with a grade I,

584
00:28:58.380 --> 00:29:00.690
there's insufficient evidence for screening

585
00:29:00.690 --> 00:29:02.490
for diabetes in children.

586
00:29:02.490 --> 00:29:05.880
So that's what you'll need to know.

587
00:29:05.880 --> 00:29:08.700
These are just some prevention things for diabetes.

588
00:29:08.700 --> 00:29:11.280
Again, it's lifestyle and weight loss.

589
00:29:11.280 --> 00:29:12.930
And those are the practice recommendations.

590
00:29:12.930 --> 00:29:14.010
So thank you very much.

591
00:29:14.010 --> 00:29:15.960
